# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coconut-milk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coconut-milk/8th-continent] 8th Continent is available in Regular Original and Vanilla, Complete Vanilla, Light Original, Vanilla and Chocolate, Fat Free Original and Vanilla.
[src:coconut-milk/8th-continent] 8th Continent is also lactose free, gluten free, and certified Vegan.
[src:coconut-milk/8th-continent] The 8th Continent worldwide headquarters is located in Santa Ana, California.
[src:coconut-milk/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:coconut-milk/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:coconut-milk/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:coconut-milk/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:coconut-milk/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:coconut-milk/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:coconut-milk/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:coconut-milk/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:coconut-milk/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:coconut-milk/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is differentiated into subtypes based on fat content.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They can be generalized into **coconut cream** (or thick coconut milk) with the highest amount of fat; coconut milk (or thin coconut milk) with a maximum of around 20% fat; and coconut skim milk with negligible amounts of fat.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut cream can be dehydrated as coconut milk powder, with a far longer shelf life.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] This terminology is not always followed in commercial coconut milk sold in Western countries.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk can also be used to produce milk substitutes (sometimes differentiated as "coconut milk beverages"); these products are meant for drinking, not cooking.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] A sweetened, processed, coconut milk product from Puerto Rico is also known as *cream of coconut*, but is distinct from coconut cream and is not interchangeable.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is used in many desserts and beverages like the piña colada.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In a 100 milliliter (ml) portion, coconut milk contains 230 kilocalories and is 68% water, 24% total fat, 6% carbohydrates, and 2% protein (table).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The fat composition includes 21 grams of saturated fat, half of which is lauric acid (table).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of manganese (40% DV per 100 g), with no other micronutrients in significant content (table for USDA source).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is a relatively stable oil-in-water emulsion with proteins that act as emulsifiers and thickening agents.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is opaque and milky white in color and ranges in consistency from watery to creamy.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Based on fat content, coconut milk is divided into different subtypes generally simplified into "coconut cream", "coconut milk", and "coconut skim milk", from highest to lowest respectively.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk and coconut cream (also called "thin coconut milk" and "thick coconut milk", respectively) are traditionally differentiated in countries where coconuts are native based on the stages of extraction.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They are also differentiated in modern standards set by the Asian and Pacific Coconut Community (APCC) and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] However, the terminologies are not always followed in commercial coconut milk (especially in western countries) because these standards are not mandatory.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] This can cause confusion among consumers.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk can also sometimes be confused with coconut water.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut water is the clear fluid found within the coconut seed, while coconut milk is the extracted liquid derived from the manual or mechanical crushing of the white inner flesh of mature coconuts.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut cream should also not be confused with creamed coconut, which is a semi-solid paste made from finely ground coconut pulp, and cream of coconut, which is a processed product made from heavily sweetened coconut cream.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is traditionally made by grating the white inner flesh of mature coconuts and mixing the shredded coconut pulp with a small amount of hot water in order to suspend the fat present in the grated pulp.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The grating process can be carried out manually or by machine.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Polynesians may use special bundles of fibre from sea hibiscus, heliconia or the coconut itself called *tauaga* to wring the milk from the meat.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is traditionally divided into two grades: coconut cream (or thick coconut milk) and thin coconut milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut cream contains around 20% to 50% fat, and (thin) coconut milk contains 5% to 20% fat.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut cream is extracted from the first pressings of grated coconut pulp directly through cheesecloth.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Sometimes a small amount of hot water is added, but usually coconut cream is extracted with no added water.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Thin coconut milk is produced by subsequent pressings after soaking the squeezed coconut pulp with hot water.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Gravity separation can also be used to derive a top layer of coconut cream and a bottom layer of coconut skim milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] This is achieved by simply allowing the extracted liquid to stand for an hour.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Conversely, coconut cream can be diluted into thinner coconut milk by simply adding water.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Traditionally prepared coconut milk is utilized immediately after being freshly extracted because it spoils easily when exposed to air.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It becomes rancid after a few hours at room temperatures 28 to 30 °C (82 to 86 °F) due to lipid oxidation and lipolysis.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Rancid coconut milk gives off a strong unpleasant smell and has a distinctive soapy taste.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] As coconut cream contains a higher amount of soluble, suspended solids, it works well as a good ingredient for desserts and rich and dry sauces.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Thinner milk contains a lesser amount of soluble solids, and is mainly used in general cooking.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The distinction between coconut cream and thin coconut milk is not usually made in western nations as fresh coconut milk is uncommon in these countries, and most consumers buy coconut milk or cream in cartons or cans.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is also an intermediate step in the traditional wet process methods of producing virgin coconut oil by gradual heating, churning, or fermentation.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] These methods, however, are less efficient than coconut oil production from copra.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut graters (also called "coconut scrapers"), a necessary tool for traditionally extracting coconut milk, were part of the material culture of the Austronesian peoples.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] From Island Southeast Asia, it was carried along with the sea voyages of the Austronesian expansion both for colonization and trade, reaching as far as Polynesia in the east, and Madagascar and the Comoros in the west in prehistoric times.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The technology also spread to non-Austronesian cultures in coastal East Africa by proximity.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Manual coconut graters remain a standard kitchen equipment in households in the tropical Asia-Pacific and Eastern Africa, underscoring the importance of coconut milk and coconut oil extraction in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The basic design of coconut graters consists of a low bench or stool with a horizontal serrated disk (made of metal in Asia and Africa, and stone or shell in Oceania) attached on one end.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] A person sits on the bench and repeatedly scrapes the inner surface of halved coconut shells with both hands over the metal disk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The scrapings are gathered by a container placed below.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] More modern mechanical coconut graters dating back to the mid-1800s consist of serrated blades with a hand crank.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] This version is believed to be a British invention.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Commercially processed coconut milk products use largely the same processes to extract coconut milk from pulp, though they use more mechanical equipment like deshelling machines, grinders and pulverizers, motorized coconut shredders, and coconut milk extractors.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They differ significantly in the bottling or canning process, however.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Processed coconut milk products are first filtered through a 100 mesh filters.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They are pasteurized indirectly by double boiling at around 70 °C (158 °F), carefully not exceeding 80 °C (176 °F), the temperature at which coconut milk starts to coagulate.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] After pasteurization, they are immediately transferred to filling vessels and sealed before being cooled down.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They are then packed into bottles, cans, or pouches and blast frozen for storage and transport.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Manufacturers of canned coconut milk typically combine diluted and comminuted milk with the addition of water as a filler.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Depending on the brand and age of the milk itself, a thicker, more paste-like consistency floats to the top of the can (a gravity separation, similar to traditional methods), and is sometimes separated and used in recipes that require coconut cream rather than coconut milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Some brands sold in Western countries undergo homogenization and contain additional thickening agents and emulsifiers to prevent the milk from separating inside the can.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Due to factors like pasteurization and minimal contact with oxygen, processed coconut milk generally has a longer shelf life than traditionally prepared coconut milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is also more efficient than traditional methods at extracting the maximum amount of coconut milk from grated coconut.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut cream can be dehydrated into coconut milk powder which has a far longer shelf life.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is produced by adding maltodextrin and casein to coconut cream to improve fluidity and then spray drying the mixture.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The powder is packaged in moisture-proof containers.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] To use, water is simply added to the coconut milk powder.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut skim milk is coconut milk with very low levels of fat (0% to 1.5%).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is a byproduct of coconut cream and coconut oil production and is usually discarded.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] However, it is increasingly being used as a food ingredient for products which require coconut flavoring without the fats (including coconut powder, coconut honey, and coconut jam).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It can also be used as a base in the production of coconut milk beverages used as milk substitutes, as it does not contain the high levels of fat characteristic of regular coconut milk while still being a good source of soluble proteins.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Processed coconut milk can be used as a substitute for milk beverages, usually marketed as "coconut milk beverage".
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They are sometimes confusingly also simply labeled as "coconut milk", though they are not the same product as coconut milk used for cooking (which is not meant for drinking).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Milk substitutes from coconut are basically coconut milk diluted with water or coconut skim milk with additives.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They contain less fat and fewer calories than milk, but also less protein.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They contain high amounts of potassium and are good sources of fiber and iron.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They are also commonly fortified with vitamin D and calcium.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is also used widely for filled milk products.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is blended with milk (usually skim milk or powdered milk) for its vegetable oils and proteins which act as substitutes for expensive butterfat in some processed milk products.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They include low-fat filled milk, evaporated reconstituted milk, and sweetened condensed milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk can also be used in cheese and custard production, substituting at most 50% of milk without lowering the overall quality of the products.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] By mixing skim milk with coconut milk, one procedure develops cheeses – including a garlic-spiced soft cheese called *queso de ajo*, a Gouda cheese substitute, and a Roquefort substitute called "Niyoblue" (a portmanteau of Tagalog: *niyog*, "coconut", and "blue").
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk can be used to enrich the fat content of soy milk, improving its texture and taste to be closer to that of real milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut cream can also be added to soy milk in the production of tofu to enrich its caloric density without affecting its palatability.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Cream of coconut is a thick, heavily sweetened, processed coconut milk product resembling condensed milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It was originally produced by the Puerto Rican company Coco López and is used most notably in piña coladas in the United States.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It can also be used for other cocktail drinks and various desserts.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is distinct from coconut cream, and is not interchangeable.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In the Philippines, coconut milk can also be further processed into coconut caramel and coconut curds, both known as *latík*.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The coconut caramel *latík* made from a reduction of muscovado sugar and coconut milk has been developed into a commercial product marketed as coconut syrup (not to be confused with coconut sugar derived from coconut sap).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] A similar product found throughout Southeast Asia is coconut jam.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is known as *matamís sa báo* in the Philippines and uses only coconut milk and sugar.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] However, the coconut jam versions from Indonesia, Malaysia, and Singapore (*kaya*); Thailand (*sangkhaya*); Cambodia (*sankiah*); and Vietnam (*banh gan*), add eggs in addition to sugar.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The latter versions are sometimes anglicized as "coconut custard" to distinguish them from the version without egg.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut jam and coconut custard have a thicker, jam-like consistency and are used as ingredients or fillings in various traditional desserts.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk can be used in both sweet and savory dishes.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In many tropical and Asian cuisines, it is a traditional ingredient in curries and other dishes, including desserts.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In Indonesia, coconut milk is used in various recipes ranging from savoury dishes – such as *rendang*, *soto*, *gulai*, *mie celor*, *sayur lodeh*, *gudeg*, *sambal goreng krechek*, and *opor ayam* – to sweet desserts, such as *serabi*, *es cendol* and *es doger*.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Soto is ubiquitous in Indonesia and considered one of Indonesia's national dishes.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] It is also used in coconut rice, a widespread Southeast Asian dish of rice cooked in coconut milk, including the *nasi lemak* of Malaysia and the *nasi uduk* of Indonesia.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In the Philippines, diverse dishes cooked in coconut milk are called *ginataán*.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] They can range from savoury dishes to desserts.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is widely used to make traditional Filipino *kakanín* (the generic term for rice pastries), including *bibingka* and *biko*, among others.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In Thailand, coconut milk is used in dishes such as *tom kha kai*, *khao tom mat*, *mango sticky rice*, and *tom yum*.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In Brazil, coconut milk is mostly used in northeastern cuisine, generally with seafood stews and desserts.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In Venezuela, pulp dishes are prepared with coconut milk and shredded fish in a dish called *mojito en coco*.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In Colombia and Panama, the grated flesh of coconut and coconut milk are used to make sweet *titoté*, a key ingredient in making *arroz con coco* (coconut rice).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is used to make traditional Venezuelan dishes, such as *majarete* (a typical Venezuelan dessert), and *arroz con coco* (the Venezuelan version of coconut rice).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In Southeast Asia, coconut milk is used to make many traditional drinks.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] *Cendol* is a popular iced drink from this region containing chilled coconut milk and green jellies made of rice flour.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconut milk is also used in hot drinks such as *bandrek* and *bajigur*, two popular drinks from Indonesia.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Aside from this, coconut milk is also an optional pairing with coffee in various countries of the region notably Vietnam (as *cà phê dừa*) plus Malaysia and Indonesia (as *kopi santan*).
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Sweetened coconut milk, and coconut milk diluted with water are two popular coconut beverages in southern China and Taiwan.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] As coconut milk becomes more popular in China, the sweetened coconut milk market is growing rapidly and is likely to reach 22.4 billion yuan (equal to about USD 3.14 billion) by 2026.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] The jelly-like pulp from the inside of the coconut is often added to coconut water to make a tropical drink.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In Brazil, for example, coconut milk is mixed with sugar and *cachaça* to make a cocktail called *batida de côco*.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Puerto Rico is also popular for tropical drinks containing coconut, such as *piña colada* and *coquito*, which typically contain coconut milk or coconut cream.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] One of the most prominent components of coconut milk is coconut oil, which many health organizations discourage people from consuming in significant amounts due to its high levels of saturated fat.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Excessive coconut milk consumption can also raise blood levels of cholesterol due to the amount of lauric acid, a saturated fat that contributes to higher blood cholesterol.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In 1943, it was discovered that coconut milk could actively encourage plant growth.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Although there are many factors that attribute coconut milk to plant growth, the main cause is the existence of a cytokinin known as zeatin found in coconut milk.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] While the zeatin in coconut milk speeds up plant growth in general, it does not speed up growth in certain plants such as radishes.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] However, when 10% coconut milk is added to the substrate on which wheat is grown, substantial improvements have been noted.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Coconuts are widely produced in tropical climates and exported globally as canned products, most frequently to North America and Europe.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] In China, coconut milk has become so popular that companies have to import coconuts from neighboring countries to meet the rising domestic demand.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] This has pushed domestic companies to explore more coconut product categories to capture market attention.
[src:coconut-milk/coconut-milk] Based on a market research study conducted by the LeadLeo Research Institute, China’s coconut-based beverage market rose from $1.5 billion to about $2.0 billion between 2017 and 2020, representing a compound annual growth rate of about 7%.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] In chemistry, the **mass fraction** of a substance within a mixture is the ratio $w_{i}$ (alternatively denoted $Y_{i}$ ) of the mass $m_{i}$ of that substance to the total mass $m_{\text{tot}}$ of the mixture.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] Mass fraction can also be expressed, with a denominator of 100, as **percentage by mass** (in commercial contexts often called *percentage by weight*, abbreviated *wt.%*, *% w/w* or *w/o*; see mass versus weight).
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] It is one way of expressing the composition of a mixture in a dimensionless size; mole fraction (percentage by moles, mol%) and volume fraction (percentage by volume, vol%) are others.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] When the prevalences of interest are those of individual chemical elements, rather than of compounds or other substances, the term *mass fraction* can also refer to the ratio of the mass of an element to the total mass of a sample.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] In these contexts an alternative term is *mass percent composition*.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] The mass fraction of an element in a compound can be calculated from the compound's empirical formula or its chemical formula.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] In thermal engineering, **vapor quality** is used for the mass fraction of vapor in the steam.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] In alloys, especially those of noble metals, the term **fineness** is used for the mass fraction of the noble metal in the alloy.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] The mass fraction is independent of temperature.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] The mixing of two pure components can be expressed introducing the (mass) mixing ratio of them $r_{m}={\frac {m_{2}}{m_{1}}}$ .
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] due to division of both numerator and denominator by the sum of masses of components.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] The mass fraction of a component in a solution is the ratio of the mass concentration of that component *ρi* (density of that component in the mixture) to the density of solution $\rho$ .
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] where $c_{i}$ is the molar concentration, and $M_{i}$ is the molar mass of the component i .
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] Mass percentage is defined as the mass fraction multiplied by 100.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] where $M_{i}$ is the molar mass of the component i , and ${\bar {M}}$ is the average molar mass of the mixture.
[src:coconut-milk/m-m] In a spatially non-uniform mixture, the mass fraction gradient gives rise to the phenomenon of diffusion.
